Enrichment Analysis of H3K27ac peaks (enhancer) with high correlation

last changed: 2023-08-29

Enrichment analysis H3K27ac enhancer (high correlation)

Data processing

To identify those enhancers with either high positive (R >= 0.7) or high negative (R <= -0.7) correlation the data frame containing those information was loaded and filtered.

> corr.enhcr <- readRDS("./../Compare_H3K27ac_RNAseq/Data/data.cor.rds")
> 
> head(corr.enhcr)
##       U2OS31     U2OS33            gene            ENSG        GHid
## 1  0.8125722  0.7161036        C1QTNF12 ENSG00000184163 GH01J037944
## 2  0.1437006  0.1469810 ENSG00000284699 ENSG00000284699 GH11J041306
## 3 -0.8981119 -0.5715487            RCC1 ENSG00000180198 GH22J028115
## 4 -0.5468799 -0.5064761           TAF12 ENSG00000120656 GH05J058261
## 5  0.4171535 -0.3878030          INPP5B ENSG00000204084 GH18J045805
## 6 -0.8669090 -0.9186477         ST3GAL3 ENSG00000126091 GH05J042894
##                      peak cluster                                 codeID
## 1  chr1:37945475-37947753       1         C1QTNF12chr1:37945475-37947753
## 2 chr11:41306087-41307140       1 ENSG00000284699chr11:41306087-41307140
## 3 chr22:28114814-28118426       1            RCC1chr22:28114814-28118426
## 4  chr5:58256648-58261930       1            TAF12chr5:58256648-58261930
## 5 chr18:45805912-45807154       1          INPP5Bchr18:45805912-45807154
## 6  chr5:42893875-42894664       1          ST3GAL3chr5:42893875-42894664
> corr.enhcr.0.7 <- corr.enhcr[which(corr.enhcr$U2OS31 %>% abs() >= 0.7 | 
+                                      corr.enhcr$U2OS33 %>% abs() >= 0.7), ]
> 
> paged_table(corr.enhcr.0.7)

In the next step, the gene IDs were translated to ENTERZ IDs, which are required for the enrichment analysis. These IDs were then added to the correlation data frame via the function inner_join, also removing duplicate entries.

> ENTREZ <- bitr(corr.enhcr.0.7$ENSG, 
+                  fromType="ENSEMBL", 
+                  toType="ENTREZID", 
+                  OrgDb="org.Hs.eg.db")
> colnames(ENTREZ) <- c("ENSG", "ID")
> 
> enhcr.ID <- inner_join(corr.enhcr, ENTREZ, multiple = "first")

Since the enrichment requires a list with the genes ordered by cluster, this was done as follows:

> list.c <- list("1" = 1, "2" = 2, "3" = 3, "4" = 4)  
> list.genes <- lapply(list.c, function(x){
+   enhcr.ID[which(enhcr.ID$cluster == x), "ID"]
+ })

Reactome Pathway enrichment analysis

Finally, the filtered list with the coding genes can be used for an enrichment analysis using the function enrichPathway, which can be plotted using dotplot.

> # Reactome Enrichment:
> PA.enhcr <- compareCluster(geneCluster = list.genes,
+                            fun = "enrichPathway",
+                            pvalueCutoff = 0.05,
+                            pAdjustMethod = "BH")
> 
> PA.enhcr %>% as.data.frame() %>% paged_table()
> dotplot(PA.enhcr, 
+         showCategory = 10, 
+         title = "Reactome Pathway Enrichment Analysis (Enhancer)")

Gene Ontology enrichment analysis

Exactly the same as above can be done with the function enrichGO.

> GO.enhcr <- compareCluster(geneCluster = list.genes,
+                            fun = "enrichGO",
+                            OrgDb = org.Hs.eg.db,
+                            ont = "BP",
+                            readable = T,
+                            pvalueCutoff = 0.05,
+                            pAdjustMethod = "BH")
> 
> GO.enhcr %>% as.data.frame() %>% paged_table()
> dotplot(GO.enhcr, 
+         showCategory = 10, 
+         title = "Gene Ontology Enrichment Analysis (Enhancer)")
